10   Appendix 3 
OUTLINE TERMS OF REFERENCE FOR CONSULTANTS 

A.  International Consultant: Institution Development and Management Expert, Team 
Leader (12 person-months) 

1.  Under the guidance of the technical assistance (TA) director, senior officials of Ministry 
of Women’s and Veterans’ Affairs (MOWVA), Asian Development Bank (ADB) staff, and in 
consultation with senior officials of the six line ministries, the consultant will: 

(i)  formulate an overall work plan and programs for the TA program; 

(ii)  provide overall direction, coordination, and management for the TA project; 

(iii)  be responsible for planning and coordinating the activities of the consultants and 
counterpart staff;  

(iv)  provide administrative management (oversight of logistic support expenses) of 
the domestic consultant and project management team, including remuneration, 
data collection and processing, procurement of office supplies, workshop and 
seminar requirements, financing, and accounting; 

(v)  ensure collaboration with the International Labor Organization (ILO) project team 
and the complementarity of all aspects of the TA with that of the Expansion of 
Employment Opportunities for Women (EEOW) and other similar projects; 

(vi)  review technical and financial sectorwide management processes of MOWVA 
and the relationship with other line ministries and provinces, and help design 
action plans for strengthening these processes; 

(vii)  review sector policies in general and subsector policies in detail in terms of 
gender  mainstreaming  and  economic  empowerment  of  women,  and  analyze 
progress, achievements, and deficiencies to date using key indicators; 

(viii)  design  a  framework  for  performance  and  program  monitoring  indicators  and 
associated data collection, provide timely feedback, and ensure that all activities 
are carried out in accordance with the work plan; 

(ix)  review the mandate, work plans, and individual job descriptions of MOWVA staff 
responsible for economic empowerment initiatives in light of the decentralization 
process; 

(x)  assess institutional capabilities of the central and provincial line ministry units in 
planning, management, and administration;  

(xi)  review  and  analyze  MOWVA’s  personal  and  financial  management  systems, 
operational procedures, marketing strategies, and human resources; 

(xii)  identify  key  sector  and  subsector  issues  and  challenges,  and  develop  an 
advocacy and strategic framework outline for development plans addressing (a) 
supply and demand of skills, (b) product marketing, (c) finance, (d) private sector 
initiatives, and (e) decentralization;
